# thinkpad-t14s — buying notes / consensus (Gen 6, 2025)
#
# config under consideration:
#   Lenovo ThinkPad T14s Gen 6, 14", Eclipse Black
#   Intel Core Ultra 7 255U (2.0 GHz)   ← NOTE: Arrow Lake-U, NOT Lunar Lake
#   32GB RAM (soldered LPDDR5x)
#   Intel integrated graphics (NOT Arc)
#   1TB SSD
#   14" WUXGA (1920x1200) display
#   WiFi 7 (802.11be), Bluetooth 5.4
#   3.08 lb (1.40 kg)
#   Windows 11 Pro
#
# consensus from reviews (Notebookcheck, PCWorld, XDA, Laptop Mag,
# Tom's Hardware): a premium, durable, quiet, all-day work laptop with a
# great keyboard and a mediocre screen, at a price that's its main
# detractor. the 32GB/1TB/Intel spec is well chosen — especially for Linux.


# THE CHIP CAVEAT (read this first — it reframes the reviews)
#
# the 255U is Intel ARROW LAKE-U, not Lunar Lake. most of the glowing
# "21-hour battery / best T14s yet" press is about either the Lunar Lake
# V-series (256V/258V) or the Snapdragon model. don't transfer that hype
# to this chip.
#
#   255U (this config)   efficiency/value tier. 12 cores (2P+8E+2LP),
#                        plain "Intel Graphics" (NOT Arc 140V), and an
#                        NPU below 40 TOPS — so NOT Copilot+ certified.
#                        good, modest, cool-running. no generational
#                        leap over Meteor Lake.
#   256V/258V (Lunar)    the battery / iGPU / AI champion the headlines
#                        rave about. different chip.
#   Snapdragon X          longest battery, cheapest — but bad for Linux
#                        (see below). avoid if you run Linux.


# CONSENSUS PROS
#
# - build & ergonomics: classic ThinkPad. carbon-fiber / magnesium,
#   ~3.08 lb, best-in-class keyboard + TrackPoint, user-replaceable
#   keyboard. universally praised.
# - runs cool, quiet, and long vs earlier T14s gens. real-world ~11+ hrs
#   (a full workday); video playback into the high teens.
# - 32GB is the right call: Intel models use SOLDERED LPDDR5x, NOT
#   upgradeable. buying 32GB now is buying it forever. done correctly.
# - WiFi 7, good port selection, serviceable (replaceable) SSD, solid 1TB.


# CONSENSUS CONS
#
# - display is the weak point: WUXGA ~400 nits, anti-glare, but reviewers
#   consistently call the colors dull / lifeless. fine for work, not for
#   media or color work.
# - price: the recurring complaint. ~$1,500-1,880 depending on sale; some
#   say the Snapdragon model does most of the job for much less.
# - Arrow Lake-U is not a performance leap over Meteor Lake.


# LINUX ANGLE (the deciding factor for this repo's use)
#
# the Intel 255U is the RIGHT T14s to buy for Linux:
# - Intel iGPU + standard x86 = excellent kernel support out of the box.
# - AVOID the Snapdragon / ARM variant for Linux — support is still rough.
# - ThinkPads are among the best-supported Linux laptops generally; this
#   one is a clean target (soldered RAM aside).
# day-one Linux checklist lives in [[fedora-to-endeavouros]]; distro
# survey in [[arch-distros]]; Fedora specifics in [[fedora]].


# BOTTOM LINE
#
# good buy for a Linux work laptop if the price is acceptable and you
# don't need a great screen or Copilot+/Arc-class graphics. just calibrate
# expectations: the 255U is the sensible/value variant, not the
# Lunar-Lake battery/AI record-setter the headlines describe.


